That's a great approach! Instead of hardcoding role-based checks into your application, you can use an external Identity Governance and Administration (IGA) or authorization system to manage your roles and their definitions. This way, you can have fine-grained access control and centralize your role management across your applications.

Here's how you can implement external role management in your ASP.NET web application:

1. Use an external authorization system: Instead of managing roles and permissions in your application, use an external authorization system that can manage access control policies and enforce them across multiple applications. You can choose an IGA solution or a cloud-based authorization service, depending on your needs.
2. Configure your application to use the authorization system: Configure your ASP.NET web application to use the external authorization system for authentication and authorization. You can use protocols like OAuth or OpenID Connect to integrate your application with the authorization system.
3. Map external roles to your application: Once you have configured your application to use the authorization system, you need to map the external roles to your application's roles. Use C# code to map external roles to your application's roles, and then use these roles to control access to pages and resources.
4. Implement fine-grained access control: With external role management in place, you can implement fine-grained access control using your defined roles and permissions. Use C# code to check if the user has the necessary permissions to view a page or UI element, using the roles and permissions defined in the external authorization system.

Here's an example of how you can check permissions using external roles and permissions:
```javascript
// Check if the user has permission to view a specific page
if (!User.HasPermission("page1_view"))
{
    // Redirect the user to an error page or display a message
    Response.Redirect("AccessDenied.aspx");
}

// Check if the user has permission to view a specific UI element
if (!User.HasPermission("button1_view"))
{
    // Hide or disable the UI element
    Button1.Visible = false;
    Button1.Enabled = false;
}
```
In this example, `User.HasPermission()` is a custom method that checks if the current user has the necessary permissions to view a specific page or UI element, using the roles and permissions defined in the external authorization system.

By using an external authorization system for role management, you can implement fine-grained access control in your ASP.NET web application, without hardcoding role-based checks into your code.

