Mockito is a popular mocking framework for Java that allows developers to create mock objects for unit testing. Here's an example of how to create a mock object using Mockito:

Suppose you have a class `UserService` that depends on another class `UserRepository` to perform some operations. You want to write a unit test for `UserService`, but you don't want to actually use a real `UserRepository` object because that would require setting up a database connection or some other resource. Instead, you can create a mock object of `UserRepository` using Mockito.

First, you need to add the Mockito dependency to your project. You can do this by adding the following to your `pom.xml` file:
```xml
<dependency>
  <groupId>org.mockito</groupId>
  <artifactId>mockito-core</artifactId>
  <version>3.11.2</version>
  <scope>test</scope>
</dependency>
```
Next, you can create a mock object of `UserRepository` in your unit test like this:
```java
import static org.mockito.Mockito.*;

...

@Test
public void testUserService() {
  // Create a mock object of UserRepository
  UserRepository userRepository = mock(UserRepository.class);

  // Create an instance of UserService with the mock UserRepository
  UserService userService = new UserService(userRepository);

  // Call a method on UserService that uses UserRepository
  userService.doSomething();

  // Verify that the method on UserRepository was called
  verify(userRepository).someMethod();
}
```
In this example, `verify` is used to check that a method on the mock object was called. You can also use Mockito to stub methods on the mock object to return specific values or throw exceptions, allowing you to simulate different scenarios in your tests.

