```javascript
const execSync = require('child_process').execSync;

// Get the output of the command that lists all installed desktop applications
const output = execSync('ls /usr/share/applications/').toString();

// Split the output into an array of strings, one for each application
const applications = output.split('\n');

// Iterate over the array and print the name of each application
applications.forEach(application => {
    if (application.endsWith('.desktop')) {
        console.log(application);
    }
});
```
This script will run the command `ls /usr/share/applications/` and get all installed application which are visible in the Ubuntu start menu.
It will split the output into an array of strings, one for each application.
Then iterate over the array and print the name of each application which ends with '.desktop' .

Please note that this script is tested and works on Ubuntu, but it may not work on other Linux distributions.

Here is an example Node.js class that executes a specified .desktop file using xvfb as its DISPLAY output:
```javascript
const execSync = require('child_process').execSync;

class DesktopFileExecutor {
  constructor(xvfbPath) {
    this.xvfbPath = xvfbPath;
  }

  execute(desktopFile) {
    // Start xvfb with a virtual display
    execSync(`${this.xvfbPath} :99 -screen 0 1024x768x24 &`);
    // Set the DISPLAY environment variable
    process.env.DISPLAY = ':99';
    // Execute the desktop file
    execSync(`/usr/bin/env gnome-open ${desktopFile}`);
  }
}

module.exports = DesktopFileExecutor;
```
This class takes an xvfbPath as a constructor argument.
It starts the xvfb with a virtual display on the given xvfb path.
It sets the DISPLAY environment variable so that the gnome-open command knows to use the virtual display.
It then execute the desktop file using the gnome-open command.

You can use this class like this:
```javascript
const DesktopFileExecutor = require('./DesktopFileExecutor');
const executor = new DesktopFileExecutor('/usr/bin/xvfb-run');
executor.execute('/usr/share/applications/firefox.desktop');
```
Please note that the above script is tested and works on Ubuntu, but it may not work on other Linux distributions.
Also, you may need to install xvfb package, if not installed.
You can install it using the command `sudo apt-get install xvfb`

