If your `facet_wrap` plot does not have labels for the facets, you can add them using the `labeller` argument and a labeller function.

Here's an example:
```scss
# Define a labeller function
my_labeller <- function(variable, value) {
  if (variable == "V1") {
    return(paste0("Dealership ", value))
  } else {
    return(as.character(value))
  }
}

ggplot(data = df, aes(x = loc, y = cars_sold)) +
  geom_col(fill = "darkblue") +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Number of Cars Sold by Dealership") +
  facet_wrap(~V1, labeller = labeller(V1 = my_labeller)) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(panel.border = element_blank(), panel.grid = element_blank(),
        strip.text = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
        axis.text.x = element_text(size = 12), axis.text.y = element_text(size = 12),
        axis.title.x = element_blank(), axis.title.y = element_blank())
```
In this example, we defined a labeller function `my_labeller` that takes two arguments: `variable` and `value`. If the `variable` is `"V1"`, which corresponds to the faceting variable in `facet_wrap()`, the function returns a string that concatenates the facet label prefix `"Dealership "` with the facet value. Otherwise, the function returns the facet value as a character.

We then passed the labeller function to the `labeller` argument of `facet_wrap()`, which replaces the default labels with the custom labels generated by the labeller function.
